10 (c) Notwithstanding sections 17 and 17.5 of this chapter, the
11 following may file a petition for sentence reduction under this
12 section:
13 (1) A convicted person described in subsection (a).
14 (2) A next friend or guardian of the convicted person.
15 (3) A treating healthcare provider of the convicted person.
16 (4) Counsel for the convicted person.
17 (d) A petition for sentence reduction must be filed with the
18 sentencing court and must contain:
19 (1) the name of the convicted person;
20 (2) the name of the petitioner and relationship of the
21 petitioner to the convicted person, if different from the
22 convicted person;
23 (3) the underlying criminal cause number and all offenses for
24 which the convicted person is serving a sentence;
25 (4) the date the convicted person was sentenced; and
26 (5) a description of:
27 (A) which sentence the convicted person seeks to be
28 reduced; and
29 (B) evidence that supports the request for sentence
30 reduction.
31 The petitioner shall serve the petition upon the department of
32 correction and the prosecuting attorney.
33 (e) A court may dismiss, without prejudice, a petition filed
34 under this section that does not comply with the requirements of
35 subsection (d). Upon receipt of a petition filed in compliance with
36 subsection (d), the court shall:
37 (1) unless impracticable, set a hearing not later than forty-five
38 (45) days after the petition is filed;
39 (2) serve notice of the hearing on:
40 (A) the petitioner;
41 (B) the convicted person, if different from the petitioner;
42 (C) counsel for the convicted person;
2026 IN 1301—LS 6989/DI 149

8
1 (D) the department of correction;
2 (E) the prosecuting attorney; and
3 (F) the victim of the convicted person (or the next of kin of
4 the victim if the conviction resulted from the death of the
5 victim), and any witness involved in the prosecution of the
6 convicted person, unless the victim or a witness has
7 requested in writing not to be notified; and
8 (3) appoint a public defender to represent the convicted
9 person if the convicted person is not represented by counsel.
10 A request for a continuance of a hearing scheduled under
11 subdivision (1) may be granted for good cause shown. An
12 individual described in subdivision (2)(F) must be notified that the
13 individual may appear in person to testify at the hearing or may
14 submit written testimony to the court.
15 (f) At a hearing on a petition for sentence reduction filed under
16 this section, the court shall consider the following:
17 (1) Rehabilitative efforts taken by the convicted person,
18 including the convicted person's participation in educational,
19 therapeutic, and vocational opportunities within the
20 department of correction.
21 (2) The length of the convicted person's sentence in
22 proportion to the risk the convicted person is to the
23 community.
24 (3) All other evidence and testimony presented in support or
25 opposition of the petition.
26 (g) If the evidence supports that the convicted person does not
27 present a significant safety risk to the community, there is a
28 rebuttable presumption that the convicted person's remaining
29 sentence should be reduced by not less than twenty percent (20%).
30 The court shall issue a final appealable order with findings of fact
31 to support the sentence reduction or the denial of the petition. If a
32 petition is granted, the court shall include:
33 (1) all time served;
34 (2) good time credit; and
35 (3) educational credit;
36 when calculating the sentence reduction.
